ments <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":12,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Hawley was born about 1278, in Grimsby, Lincolnshire, England, his father, Lord Robert Hawley, was 24 and his mother, Lady Martha Hawley, was 24. He married Joan Girsby in 1302, in Burgh on Bain, Lincolnshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1309, in Burgh on Bain, Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 32."},"et":{"about 1278–1309":"umbes 1278–1309","1278–1309":"1278–1309","1282–1310":"1282–1310","1310–1387":"1310–1387","1255–1310":"1255–1310","1255–1305":"1255–1305","1305":"1305","1302":"1302","1278":"1278","1255":"1255","1387":"1387","1310":"1310","about 1278":"umbes 1278","1309":"1309","1282":"1282","1290":"1290","Burgh on Bain, Lincolnshire, England":"Burgh on Bain, Lincolnshire, England","Grimsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Grimsby, Lincolnshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1278–1309":"noin 1278–1309","1278–1309":"1278–1309","1282–1310":"1282–1310","1310–1387":"1310–1387","1255–1310":"1255–1310","1255–1305":"1255–1305","1305":"1305","1302":"1302","1278":"1278","1255":"1255","1387":"1387","13